en","1510–1559":"1510–1559","1512–1574":"1512–1574","1474–1525":"1474–1525","Cir 1507":"1507","Cir 1512":"1512","1472":"1472","1525":"1525","1512":"1512","Abt. 1525":"circa 1525","1510":"1510","June 1505":"juni 1505","1574":"1574","1474":"1474","1507":"1507","1529":"1529","1505":"1505","1559":"1559","Enville, Staffordshire, England":"Enville, Staffordshire, England","Whittington, Enville, Staffordshire, England":"Enville, Staffordshire, England","West Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Whothington Stafford":"Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wooten, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1474–Abt. 1525":"1474–about 1525","1472–1529":"1472–1529","1505–Female":"1505–Deceased","1507–Female":"1507–Deceased","1510–1559":"1510–1559","1512–1574":"1512–1574","1474–1525":"1474–1525","Cir 1507":"1507","Cir 1512":"1512","1472":"1472","1525":"1525","1512":"1512","Abt. 1525":"about 1525","1510":"1510","June 1505":"June 1505","1574":"1574","1474":"1474","1507":"1507","1529":"1529","1505":"1505","1559":"1559","Enville, Staffordshire, England":"Enville, Staffordshire, England","Whittington, Enville, Staffordshire, England":"Enville, Staffordshire, England","West Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Whothington Stafford":"Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Wooten, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Middleton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so called. In over thirty instances from many different areas, the name is from Old English <i>midel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. However, Middleton on the Hill near Leominster in Herefordshire appears in Domesday Book as <i>Miceltune</i>, the first element clearly being Old English <i>micel</i> ‘large’, ‘great’ (see   Middlebrook  ). Middleton Baggot and Middleton Priors in Shropshire have early spellings that suggest <i>gem̄thhyll</i> (from <i>gem̄th</i> ‘confluence’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’) + <i>tūn</i> as the origin. This surname is also found in Scotland and Ireland.","History: A Scottish family of this name derives it from lands at Middleto(u)n near Kincardine. The Scottish physician Peter Middleton practiced in New York City after 1752 and was one of the founders of the medical school at King's College (now Columbia University) in 1767. One of the earliest of the Charleston, SC, Middleton family of prominent legislators was Arthur Middleton, born in Charleston in 1681. The name has also been established in Ireland since at least the 13th century; its presence was reinforced by settlers in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Midthun","meanings":["Norwegian: habitational name from any of about ten farmsteads in western Norway named Midtun, from Old Norse <i>mith</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tún</i> ‘enclosure, farmstead’. Compare   Middleton  ."]},{"name":"Melton","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from any of various places, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire, all of which have the same origin as   Middleton  , with Old English <i>middel</i> replaced by its Old Norse equivalent <i>methal</i> after the Scandinavian settlement of northern and eastern England."]},{"name":"Middlebrook","meanings":["English: habitational name from a lost <i>Micklebrook</i> in Blackburn (Lancashire), recorded as <i>Mikelbroc</i> in the 13th century. The placename appears to derive from Old English <i>micel</i> ‘big’ + <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’. The surname has undergone a dissimilatory or folk-etymological change from <i>Mickle-</i> to <i>Middle-</i>."]},{"name":"Milton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from one or other of the many places called Milton, or sometimes Middleton (see   Middleton  ) and occasionally Melton (see   Melton  ), most of which derive from Old English <i>middel</i> ‘middle’ or <i>myln</i> ‘mill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]},{"name":"Harewell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","variant of   Farwell   2.","from the Middle English phrase <i>fare wel</i> ‘do well, prosper’, or perhaps from the saluation <i>fare wel</i> ‘farewell, goodbye’."],"variants":[{"name":"Farwell","meanings":["Irish: Fearn, a shield, and aille, beautiful, meaning a beautiful shield"]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anne Harewell Middleton was born in 1474, in Yorkshire, England. She married Sir Edward Grey in June 1505, in Staffordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died about 1525, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1474–Abt. 1525":"1474–umbes 1525","1472–1529":"1472–1529","1505–Female":"1505–Surnud","1507–Female":"1507–Surnud","1510–1559":"1510–1559","1512–1574":"1512–1574","1474–1525":"1474–1525","Cir 1507":"1507","Cir 1512":"1512","1472":"1472","1525":"1525","1512":"1512","Abt. 1525":"umbes 1525","1510":"1510","June 1505":"juuni 1505","1574":"1574","1474":"1474","1507":"1507","1529":"1529","1505":"1505","1559":"1559","Enville, Staffordshire, England":"Enville, Staffordshire, England","Whittington, Enville, Staffordshire, England":"Enville, Staffordshire, England","West Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Whothington Stafford":"Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wooten, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1474–Abt. 1525":"1474–noin 1525","1472–152